today i learned the hard way, printing a sphere-like object is very difficult!
mine looks more like an egg :-/
so not only the general calibration must be fine, but also the supports must be set right!!

with this sphere you can experiment with...

  • more/less perimeters
  • with/without automated supports
  • manually generate few/lot supports only on one side of one axis. example: you only add support to the left side of the x- and y-axis, but none to the right side. that way you will encounter the results with ONE print and you don't have to print many of them.

to change your settings, please look at the original calibration cube for more information

IMPORTANT:
with most slicers you can add a brim automatically by enabling skirt/brim and set the distance to print to 0mm
in case it doesn't work, i added a second version with a 20mm brim ;-)

First Test:

  • 1st quarter - little bit of supports
  • 2nd + 3rd quarter - no support at all
  • 4th quarter - lots of support!!
  • <10% infill
  • part cooling active

Learned so far:
support ist VERY helfpull in terms of cooling the perimeters down! even my part cooling fan was not enough to compensate the remaining heat in the print. so the perimeter walls were still too hot to become solid before the next layer was printed. as an result, the print failed in the 1st, 2nd, and 3rd quarter. the 4th quarter had lots of support, so the perimeter had enough time to cool down and remain its shape.

Result & Solutions:

  • reduce heat!!
  • if you want to print a small sphere-like object, make sure, the material has enough time to cool down befor the next layer will be printed.
  • --> print multible parts the same time! so the printer has to leave that one object alone for a while and it can cool down
  • --> reduce the temprature of your printer and printbed.
  • --> add an additional part cooling fan. even a hand-ventilator from summer helps ^^

  • Print the case
  • Disassemble the charger, and remove the electronics inside.

  • Insert the new unit into the battery case. You may need to either adjust or shave the posts to ensure a good fit. I have included the bottom .sldprt for you to modify if you need to for your specific application.
  • When ready to charge, plug in the 9v battery.

description.text:
This tool is designed to apply an even, precise amount of grease to the splines in the tail rotor driveshaft couplings on the Bell 206 helicopter. Measurements were taken from the BHT service manual, but while the typical tool uses only one "face" this tool uses 4 faces. This both makes the tool much easier to use and keeps it perfectly aligned in the coupling, ensuring even coverage. The tool is simply inserted, rotated, and removed with any excess grease

The handle was generated using Neon22's "Customizable Profiled Handle" http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:923244

I recommend printing the tool standing upright with supports, some cleanup will be necessary but this seems to result in the nicest looking finished product.

description.text:
Do you hate support and the scars removing it leaves on a beautiful model? Do you wish to print the handsome Ares scan taller than your printer allows? I cut the model into three pieces so you can print them perfectly without support and make it taller than your printer allows. The model is scale down to 27% (no detail is lost in downscaling).

Print in original orientation and you won't need support. The only (important) place that has extreme overhang is behind Ares' ears, but it's not too bad, and in fact you could also use a little bit of support there. But I was able to print the model without support and get very good result. Sand the glue surface a little bit, and glue with E6000 easily. (Superglue is dangerous because it bonds too quickly for fine alignment adjustments.)

Possibly due to shrinkage, the bottom of the head piece is slightly smaller than the top of the chest piece. But overall it worked very well. Without support, the face and Mohawk are scar-free.

ENG - Hello this is my first selfmade design.

This is a luggage anchor, its designed to hold everything in place in the back of your trunk when you accidentally misjudged turn a 'little' or when you are transporting fragile things. the resolution of the print does not have to be so high but you can tweak the settings to your liking of course. there are 2 versions, one of 10 centimeters (3.937007874 inches) tall, and one of 15 centimeters (5.905511811 inches) tall. If you guys have any remarks or want to see something changed please leave me some feed back and i will see what I can do. Thank you ~ Sorry for bad photo's its hard to get a good picture of black objects as soon as i get new filament i will take new ones.

Steps:

  1. Print the part(s)
  2. Buy some velcro + Some glue that will stick well to ABS or PETG
  3. Glue the velcro on to the marked place "place velcro here"
  4. Try it out! and maybe leave me some feedback

NL - Hallo dit is mijn aller eerste zelf gemaakte design.

Dit is een bagage-anker, deze zijn bedoelt om dingen die achter in je kofferbak liggen op hun plek te houden wanneer je per ongeluk een bocht 'iets' hebt onderschat, of als je breekbaar spul transporteert. De resolutie van deze print hoeft niet zo heel hoog te zijn maar kan naar eigen smaak altijd veranderd worden natuurlijk. Er zijn 2 versies, een van 10 centimeter lang en een van 15 centimeter lang. Als jullie nog tips of misschien zelfs iets verandert zouden willen zien laat het me het dan graag weten en dan zal ik kijken wat ik er aan kan doen. Dank jullie wel ~ Sorry voor de slechte fotos het is nog al moeilijk om een mooie foto van zwarte objecten te maken ik maak nieuwe zodra ik nieuwe filament heb.

Stappen:

title: Remix of Self locking Kossel mini carriage with Variable Beltway Width

description.text:
I like these self locking belt clamps, but 2.5mm works better for me than the original 2.2mm.

I am using this on a Folger Tech Kossel 2020 & used the geometry from my previous remix http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:1793640 & used the self locking belt clamp idea from http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:556178

I made the nut trap for the locknuts so they are easier to insert without going thru the beltway. There is also a small hole on the bottom of each nut trap to make it easier to eject the locknut with a small allen wrench if you need to take the locknut out.

There are a few variables in the openscad file you can change, but the main 2 variables you might change are:

Gap_Tighten_Wid = 2.5; //2.2 was the original size

Lt_Rt_Both = -1; //-1 = Left Bottom Mount Hole Only
//0 = Both Left & Right Mount holes
//1 = Right Bottom Mount Hole Only

I printed this with eSun PLA+ Silver at 50% infill.

title: iPhone 6 RBS Train Seat Backrest Clip

description.text:
I have a 40 minute train ride to commute to work every day and I wanted a way to mount my iPhone 6 to the backrest of the seat in front of me so I could watch stuff without having to hold the phone. So I created a holder that clips on the phone and slides in the little gap between the frame and the cushion in the backrest of the seat in front of me.

This is customized for my own phone with a thin 0.3mm case - so I added 1mm to the width - and the backrest of an RBS train in Bern, Switzerland. It is therefore obviously a very specific design. I figured I'll upload it anyways, maybe someone can get some use out of it or adjust it for their own use.

The design is heavily inspired by the iPhone hook for airplanes by jgrout (http://www.thingiverse.com/thing:8214), but I - or more specifically my significant other with actual 3d design skills - redesigned it from scratch for my specific use.

print_settings.Notes:: Very simple print. All three pieces can be done at once.

description.text:
This is a lens filter assembly that I made for the Xiaomi Yi camera. It prints in three separate printer-friendly pieces that must be glues together. A filter of your choice (ND, polarizer) is inserted between the main housing and top ring.

The size of this filter allows the use of the Yi's complete 120 degree field of view without having any vignetting on the image. It is just about as wide as the Yi is tall so the camera will still sit upright on a flat surface.

I decided to make my own filter after not finding a suitable one online. The filters I found for sale were said to add vignetting to the video, and the ones that were large enough to avoid this issue would take weeks to arrive. So I made my own design and used the polarized lens from an old pair of 3D movie glasses.

Printer:

FolgerTech 2020

Rafts:

No

Supports:

No

Resolution:

0.1-0.2mm

Infill:

Any Amount

Notes:

Very simple print. All three pieces can be done at once.

Finishing

If you did not use a glass bed to print on, you may want to sand down the bottoms of each part so that things will be as flush as possible when gluing together the final filter.

Using the main filter body, cut out a piece of filter material of equal diameter. When gluing the top ring on to the main filter body sandwich the filter in between the two pieces. Make sure not to use too much glue or else there will be overflow on to the filter. I used a very thin layer of hot glue. Since the filter does not receive a lot of stress hot glue should hold just fine.

title: Mavic by mwilmar rear arms w/ less supports

description.text: The original rear arms had a lot of supports and a long print time. I removed the landing leg and removed a section of the front part of the arm which is then glued on after printing. This way saves a lot of time and the print looks much better under the part were the supports would be. I opted to leave the landing leg off of the rear leg to make it look more like the real Mavic.

There are two supports to pop off and one small piece that is glued on. I use CA glue or that same is superglue.

The pivot pins will most likely need some filing and/or sanding to get them to pivot freely in the lock blocks. This is due to the pins being printed horizontal. A little bit of light oil helps also.

title: Portaberry Pi Ultra (Portable Rpi Game Emulator)

description.text:
Introducing the Portaberry Pi Ultra my newest Raspberry Pi powered portable emulator console! It is the spiritual successor to the original Portaberry Pi with a host of updates and improvements to make it an extremely versatile video gaming machine. For more information check the quick start guide HERE.

About:
The aim here was to build on my previous experience with raspberry pi consoles to make a sleek and easy to build console that packed as many features as possible including: full modern controls, large HDMI display, speakers/headphone jack and large battery life. This console should be able to take advantage of newer Retropie emulators including the N64 and PS1 as well as any older system emulator.

Features:
-5" HDMI Display
-Full complement of modern controls (2 analog sticks, d-pad, 4 action buttons, start/select, and L/R shoulder and trigger buttons)
-Raspberry Pi 2 Running Retropie 4.1
-Stereo Speakers and headphone jack
-4400mAh battery giving roughly 4 to 5 hours of play time
-USB micro charging input using Adafruit Powerboost1000c
-Wooden laser cut front and rear panels

Instructions:
For those of you interested in building your own I recommend reading the Getting Started Guide first. Following this check out the Build Log to get a feel for what the build entails. Finally check out the Bill of Material for links to all necessary components.

IMPORTANT
These instructions are in a very early state. Some detail is missing which I am working day by day to improve. They also have not had a chance to be checked. If you decide to build your own Portaberry Pi Ultra please be sure to check through the instructions thoroughly for any incorrect or confusing steps. If you find any let me know in the comments and I will work to correct the issue.

Modifying this design:
I openly invite anyone who wants to to modify/improve this design as they see fit. To aid in this I've added a zip file in the Thing File tab with a STEP file of every part of the case. All I ask is that modifications be logged as remixes of this design so that any improvements can be easily tracked and accessed. Also just gimme some credit if you can :P

comments.text: Awesome.  Simple and no bearings.  Have been on the stock spool holders and it was getting to be a pain changing and getting the width just right for the different spools.  If I had 1 comment it's that on my frame at least (mk2s) it sits kind of loose.  I had to add 3 layers of scotch tape at 2 places and now it's snug.  When I removed the spool the holder was coming off as well.  I think maybe the slot needs to be 0.5 to 1mm thinner but I will not bother to reprint it.
comments.author: hulabaloo

comments.text: is it possible to get one that about that's about a quarter to a half  inch taller (the distance from the spool holder and the frame attach point)? works great for most spools, but i have a couple that drag on the bottom, nothing that the extruder cant fight through, so, its working, but not as well as id prefer
comments.author: TrackerF16

comments.text: Yes, that's definitely possible. I uploaded a v2, which is 15mm taller (~0.6") than before. It also attempts to correct an issue where the x-carriage would get caught on the front plane of the spool holder if the Z-axis was all the way up, by making this part thinner. This may make it a little more fragile, but it was a necessary change.
